				\begin{document}$${\text{Cs}}_{0.05} \left[ {{\text{FA}}_{0.83} {\text{MA}}_{0.17} } \right]_{0.95} {\text{Pb}}\left[ {{\text{I}}_{0.83} {\text{Br}}_{0.17} } \right]_{3}$$\end{document} (CsFAMA) was chosen as the photoactive material because of its long-term stability and high performance in photovoltaics [16]. As shown by Patil et al. [17], adding a small amount of thiourea (TU) into the perovskite precursor can massively increase the size of the crystallites in the thin film. Therefore, 15 vol.% of a 1.5 M TU solution were added to the perovskite precursor prior to spin-coating onto indium tin oxide (ITO) substrates. These large-grain perovskite thin films are, besides their reported superior photovoltaic characteristics, of fundamental interest as they provide atomically flat grain facets on the scale of several µm2, which is ideal for a homogenous growth of the thermally deposited acceptor molecules. The organic molecule perylene-3,4,9,10-tetracarboxylic dianhydride (PTCDA) was selected as a strong electron acceptor that exhibits high stability in ultra-high vacuum and under 1.5 suns illumination.
